item.title: Chicken Roasted Meat
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded: My family always ate a very traditional meal on Thanksgiving: mashed potatoes with gravy, green been casserole, roasted sweet potatoes studded with marshmallows. So like the good little rebel I was, for one of my first holiday meals outside the family, I decided to forgo the classics.

item.title: Chinese Mix Food
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded: PREP THE FILLING Chop or shred leftover roasted vegetables or meat scraps (turkey, steak dinner, chili, pulled pork, or carnitas would all work).

item.title: Crossant
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded: COVER AND ROAST Puree extra baked potatoes, leftover roasted root vegetables, or I don't know, actual mashed potatoes, into a creamy topping. Smooth over the filling, then added a sprinkling of cheese. Bake until golden brown on top, around 30 minutes.

item.title: Prawn
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded:
Thanksgiving Day is great and all, don't get me wrong.
But I spend most of the meal looking forward to something that happens 6-24 hours later. An event so joyous that members of my family have battled over both who takes the lead on it and when, exactly, it happens for generations.

item.title: Lamb Stack
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded: THEORY: LEG MEAT IS THE BEST MEAT You've likely got leftover parts from all over the turkey, but for the purposes of a leftovers sandwich you want to zero in on the juicy, flavorful dark meat from the turkey's leg.

item.title: Restaurant Enviornment
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded: If you're staring down the barrel of a bowl of sad, lumpy mashed potatoes it might already be too late. I say might because you may be able to save them: Try passing those less-than-ideal spuds through a potato ricer to smooth out the chunky bits.

item.title: Lamb Curry
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded: Listen, I'm all about mayo on almost every single sandwich I write about for this column, but the leftovers sandwich is one case where it's just not necessary. Why? Because you have gravy. Rich, thick, buttery gravy.

item.title: Lamp Roast
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded: THEORY: THE MASHED POTATOES MUST BE SMOOTH If you're staring down the barrel of a bowl of sad, lumpy mashed potatoes it might already be too late. I say might because you may be able to save them: Try passing those less-than-ideal spuds through a potato ricer to smooth out the chunky bits.

item.title: Make Pizza
item.dc:creator: admin
item.content:encoded: THEORY: SKIP LEAFY GREENS, OPT FOR GREEN BEANS No need to head to the store for a clamshell of arugula or spring mixjust grab a handful of leftover sauted green beans for crunch, color, and the ability to feel a bit better about eating three of these things.
